# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electronic-control-unit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:electronic-control-unit/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:electronic-control-unit/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:electronic-control-unit/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:electronic-control-unit/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:electronic-control-unit/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:electronic-control-unit/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:electronic-control-unit/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:electronic-control-unit/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:electronic-control-unit/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:electronic-control-unit/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:electronic-control-unit/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:electronic-control-unit/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:electronic-control-unit/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:electronic-control-unit/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] An **anti-lock braking system** (**ABS**) is a safety anti-skid braking system used on aircraft and on land vehicles, such as cars, motorcycles, trucks, and buses.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS operates by preventing the wheels from locking up during braking, thereby maintaining tractive contact with the road surface and allowing the driver to maintain more control over the vehicle.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS is an automated system that uses the principles of threshold braking and cadence braking, techniques which were once practiced by skillful drivers before ABS was widespread.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS operates at a much faster rate and more effectively than most drivers could manage.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Although ABS generally offers improved vehicle control and decreases stopping distances on dry and some slippery surfaces, on loose gravel or snow-covered surfaces ABS may significantly increase braking distance, while still improving steering control.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Since ABS was introduced in production vehicles, such systems have become increasingly sophisticated and effective.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Modern versions may not only prevent wheel lock under braking, but may also alter the front-to-rear brake bias.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This latter function, depending on its specific capabilities and implementation, is known variously as electronic brakeforce distribution, traction control system, emergency brake assist, or electronic stability control (ESC).
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The concept for ABS predates the modern systems that were introduced in the 1950s.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Francis introduced his 'Slip Prevention Regulator for Rail Vehicles'.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1920 the French automobile and aircraft pioneer Gabriel Voisin experimented with systems that modulated the hydraulic braking pressure on his aircraft brakes to reduce the risk of tire slippage, as threshold braking on aircraft is nearly impossible.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] These systems used a flywheel and valve attached to a hydraulic line that feeds the brake cylinders.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The flywheel is attached to a drum that runs at the same speed as the wheel.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In normal braking, the drum and flywheel should spin at the same speed.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] However, when a wheel slows down, then the drum would do the same, leaving the flywheel spinning at a faster rate.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This causes the valve to open, allowing a small amount of brake fluid to bypass the master cylinder into a local reservoir, lowering the pressure on the cylinder and releasing the brakes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The use of the drum and flywheel meant the valve only opened when the wheel was turning.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In testing, a 30% improvement in braking performance was noted, because the pilots immediately applied full brakes instead of slowly increasing pressure in order to find the skid point.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] An additional benefit was the elimination of burned or burst tires.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The first proper recognition of the ABS system came later with the German engineer Karl Wässel, whose system for modulating braking power was officially patented in 1928.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Wässel, however, never developed a working product and neither did Robert Bosch who produced a similar patent eight years later.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] A similar braking system called Decelostat that used direct-current generators to measure wheel slippage was used in railroads in the 1930s.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] By 1951, flywheel-based Decelostat was used in aircraft to provide anti skid in landings.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The device was on trials first in the United States and later by the British.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1954, *Popular Science* revealed that there was preliminary testing of the Decelostat system to prevent car swirling on a heavy brake by the US car manufacturers in Detroit.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] However, there was no public information of the test results.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Maxaret, while reducing braking distances by up to 30% in icy or wet conditions, also increased tire life, and had the additional advantage of allowing take-offs and landings in conditions that would preclude flying at all in non-Maxaret equipped aircraft.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1958, a Royal Enfield Super Meteor motorcycle was used by the Road Research Laboratory to test the Maxaret anti-lock brake.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The experiments demonstrated that anti-lock brakes can be of great value to motorcycles, for which skidding is involved in a high proportion of accidents.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Stopping distances were reduced in most of the tests compared with locked wheel braking, particularly on slippery surfaces, in which the improvement could be as much as 30%.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Enfield's technical director at the time, Tony Wilson-Jones, saw little future in the system, however, and it was not put into production by the company.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] A fully-mechanical system saw limited automobile use in the 1960s in the Ferguson P99 racing car, the Jensen FF, and the experimental all-wheel drive Ford Zodiac, but saw no further use; the system proved expensive and unreliable.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The first fully-electronic anti-lock braking system was developed in the late-1960s for the Concorde aircraft.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The modern ABS system was invented in 1971 by Mario Palazzetti (known as 'Mister ABS') in the Fiat Research Center and has become standard in almost every car.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The system was called Antiskid and the patent was sold to Bosch who named it ABS.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Chrysler, together with the Bendix Corporation, introduced a computerized, three-channel, four-sensor all-wheel ABS called "Sure Brake" for its 1971 Imperial.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] It was available for several years thereafter, functioned as intended, and proved reliable.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1969, Ford introduced an anti-lock braking system called "Sure-Track" to the rear wheels of the Lincoln Continental Mark III and Ford Thunderbird, as an option; it became standard in 1971.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The Sure-Track braking system was designed with help from Kelsey-Hayes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1971, General Motors introduced the "Trackmaster" rear-wheel only ABS as an option on their rear-wheel drive Cadillac models and called the option the True-Track Braking System on the Oldsmobile Toronado.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1972, the option was made available in all Cadillacs.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1971, Nissan offered an EAL (Electro Anti-lock System) developed by Japanese company Denso as an option on the Nissan President, which became Japan's first electronic ABS.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] 1971: The Imperial became the first production car with a 4 wheel computer-operated anti-lock braking system.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Toyota introduced electronically controlled anti-skid brakes on Toyota Crown labeled as ESC (Electronic Skid Control).
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] 1971: First truck application: "Antislittamento" system developed by *Fiat Veicoli Industriali* and installed on Fiat truck model 691N1.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] 1972: four-wheel-drive Triumph 2500 Estates were fitted with Mullard electronic systems as standard.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Such cars were rare however and very few remain.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] 1976: WABCO began the development of the anti-locking braking system on commercial vehicles to prevent locking on slippery roads, followed in 1986 by the electronic braking system (EBS) for heavy-duty vehicles.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] 1978: Mercedes-Benz W116 As one of the firsts, used an electronic four-wheel multi-channel anti-lock braking system (ABS) from Bosch as an option from 1978 on.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] 1982: Honda introduced electronically controlled multi-channel ALB (Anti Locking Brakes) as an option for the second generation of Prelude, launched worldwide in 1982.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Additional info: the general agent for Honda in Norway required all Preludes for the Norwegian market to have the ALB-system as a standard feature, making Honda Prelude be the first car delivered in Europe with ABS as a standard feature.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The Norwegian general agent also included a sunroof and other options to be standard equipment in Norway, adding more luxury to the Honda brand.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] However, the Norwegian tax system made the well-equipped car very expensive, and the sales suffered from high costs.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] From 1984 the ALB-system, as well as the other optional features from Honda, was no longer a standard feature in Norway.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1985 the Ford Scorpio was introduced to the European market with a Teves electronic system throughout the range as standard.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] For this the model was awarded the coveted European Car of the Year Award in 1986, with very favorable praise from motoring journalists.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] After this success, Ford began research into Anti-Lock systems for the rest of their range, which encouraged other manufacturers to follow suit.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Since 1987 ABS has been standard equipment on all Mercedes-Benz automobiles.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1988, BMW introduced the first motorcycle with an electro-hydraulic ABS: the BMW K100.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Yamaha Introduced the FJ1200 model with optional ABS in 1991.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Honda followed suit in 1992 with the launch of its first motorcycle ABS on the ST1100 Pan European.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In 2007, Suzuki launched its GSF1200SA (Bandit) with an ABS.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In 2005, Harley-Davidson began offering an ABS option on police bikes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The anti-lock brake controller is also known as the CAB (Controller Anti-lock Brake).
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Typically ABS includes a central electronic control unit (ECU), four wheel speed sensors, and at least two hydraulic valves within the brake hydraulics.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Conversely, if the ECU detects a wheel turning significantly faster than the others, brake hydraulic pressure to the wheel is increased so the braking force is reapplied, slowing down the wheel.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This process is repeated continuously and can be detected by the driver via brake pedal pulsation.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Some anti-lock systems can apply or release braking pressure 15 times per second.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Because of this, the wheels of cars equipped with ABS are practically impossible to lock even during panic braking in extreme conditions.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The ECU is programmed to disregard differences in wheel rotative speed below a critical threshold because when the car is turning, the two wheels towards the center of the curve turn slower than the outer two.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] For this same reason, a differential is used in virtually all roadgoing vehicles.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] If a fault develops in any part of the ABS, a warning light will usually be illuminated on the vehicle instrument panel, and the ABS will be disabled until the fault is rectified.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Modern ABS applies individual brake pressure to all four wheels through a control system of hub-mounted sensors and a dedicated micro-controller.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS is offered or comes standard on most road vehicles and is the foundation for electronic stability control systems, which are rapidly increasing in popularity due to the great reduction in the price of vehicle electronics over the years.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Modern electronic stability control (ESC) systems are an evolution of the ABS concept.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Here, a minimum of two additional sensors are added to help the system work: these are a steering wheel angle sensor and a gyroscopic sensor.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The steering wheel sensor also helps in the operation of Cornering Brake Control (CBC), since this will tell the ABS that wheels on the inside of the curve should brake more than wheels on the outside, and by how much.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS equipment may also be used to implement a traction control system (TCS) on the acceleration of the vehicle.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] If, when accelerating, the tire loses traction, the ABS controller can detect the situation and take suitable action so that traction is regained.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] More sophisticated versions of this can also control throttle levels and brakes simultaneously.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The speed sensors of ABS are sometimes used in indirect tire pressure monitoring system (TPMS), which can detect under-inflation of the tire(s) by the difference in the rotational speed of wheels.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] There are four main components of ABS: wheel speed sensors, valves, a pump, and a controller.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] A speed sensor is used to determine the acceleration or deceleration of the wheel.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The rotation of the wheel or differential induces a magnetic field around the sensor.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The fluctuations of this magnetic field generate a voltage in the sensor.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Since the voltage induced in the sensor is a result of the rotating wheel, this sensor can become inaccurate at slow speeds.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The slower rotation of the wheel can cause inaccurate fluctuations in the magnetic field and thus cause inaccurate readings to the controller.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] There is a valve in the brake line of each brake controlled by the ABS.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The majority of problems with the valve system occur due to clogged valves.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] When a valve is clogged it is unable to open, close, or change position.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] An inoperable valve will prevent the system from modulating the valves and controlling pressure supplied to the brakes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The pump in the ABS is used to restore the pressure to the hydraulic brakes after the valves have released it.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] A signal from the controller will release the valve at the detection of wheel slip.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] After a valve releases the pressure supplied from the user, the pump is used to restore the desired amount of pressure to the braking system.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The controller will modulate the pump's status in order to provide the desired amount of pressure and reduce slipping.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] type unit in the car which receives information from each individual wheel speed sensor.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] If a wheel loses traction, the signal is sent to the controller.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The controller will then limit the brake force (EBD) and activate the ABS modulator which actuates the braking valves on and off.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] There are many different variations and control algorithms for use in ABS.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The ABS controller knows that such a rapid deceleration of the car is impossible (and in actuality the rapid deceleration means the wheel is about to slip), so it reduces the pressure to that brake until it sees an acceleration, then it increases the pressure until it sees the deceleration again.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] It can do this very quickly before the wheel can actually significantly change speed.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The result is that the wheel slows down at the same rate as the car, with the brakes keeping the wheels very near the point at which they will start to lock up.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This gives the system maximum braking power.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This replaces the need to manually pump the brakes while driving on a slippery or a low traction surface, allowing to steer even in most emergency braking conditions.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] When the ABS is in operation the driver will feel a pulsing in the brake pedal; this comes from the rapid opening and closing of the valves.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This pulsing also tells the driver that the ABS has been triggered.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Anti-lock braking systems use different schemes depending on the type of brakes in use.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] They can be differentiated by the number of channels: that is, how many valves that are individually controlled—and the number of speed sensors.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] There is a speed sensor on all four wheels and a separate valve for all four wheels.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] With this setup, the controller monitors each wheel individually to make sure it is achieving maximum braking force.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] There is a speed sensor on all four wheels and a separate valve for each of the front wheels, but only one valve for both of the rear wheels.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Older vehicles with four-wheel ABS usually use this type.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This scheme, commonly found on pickup trucks with four-wheel ABS, has a speed sensor and a valve for each of the front wheels, with one valve and one sensor for both rear wheels.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The speed sensor for the rear wheels is located in the rear axle.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This system provides individual control of the front wheels, so they can both achieve maximum braking force.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The rear wheels, however, are monitored together; they both have to start to lock up before the ABS will activate on the rear.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] With this system, it is possible that one of the rear wheels will lock during a stop, reducing brake effectiveness.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This system is easy to identify, as there are no individual speed sensors for the rear wheels.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This system, commonly found on passenger cars from the late '80s through the mid-1990s, uses a speed sensor at each wheel, with one control valve each for the front and rear wheels as a pair.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] If the speed sensor detects lock up at any individual wheel, the control module pulses the valve for both wheels on that end of the car.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This system is commonly found on pickup trucks, SUVs, and vans with rear-wheel ABS.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] It has one valve, which controls both rear wheels, and a one-speed sensor, for the rear axle.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This system operates the same as the rear end of a three-channel system.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The rear wheels are monitored together and they both have to start to lock up before the ABS kicks in.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In this system it is also possible that one of the rear wheels will lock, reducing brake effectiveness.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This system is also easy to identify, as there are no individual speed sensors for any of the wheels.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] On high-traction surfaces such as bitumen, or concrete, many (though not all) ABS-equipped cars are able to attain braking distances better (i.e. shorter) than those that would be possible without the benefit of ABS.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In real-world conditions, even an alert and experienced driver without ABS would find it difficult to match or improve on the performance of a typical driver with a modern ABS-equipped vehicle.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS reduces the chances of crashing, and/or the severity of impact.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The recommended technique for non-expert drivers in an ABS-equipped car, in a typical full-braking emergency, is to press the brake pedal as firmly as possible and, where appropriate, to steer around obstructions.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In such situations, ABS will significantly reduce the chances of a skid and subsequent loss of control.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In gravel, sand, and deep snow, ABS tends to increase braking distances.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] On these surfaces, locked wheels dig in and stop the vehicle more quickly.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Some ABS calibrations reduce this problem by slowing the cycling time, thus letting the wheels repeatedly briefly lock and unlock.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Some vehicle manufacturers provide an "off-road" button to turn the ABS function off.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The primary benefit of ABS on such surfaces is to increase the ability of the driver to maintain control of the car rather than go into a skid, though the loss of control remains more likely on soft surfaces such as gravel or on slippery surfaces such as snow or ice.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] On a very slippery surface such as sheet ice or gravel, it is possible to lock multiple wheels at once, and this can defeat ABS (which relies on comparing all four wheels and detecting individual wheels skidding).
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The availability of ABS relieves most drivers from learning threshold braking.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] A June 1999 National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) study found that ABS increased stopping distances on loose gravel by an average of 27.2 percent.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] When activated, some earlier ABSes caused the brake pedal to pulse noticeably.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] As most drivers rarely or do not brake hard enough to cause brake lock-up, and drivers typically do not read the vehicle's owner's manual, this may not be noticeable until an emergency.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Some manufacturers have therefore implemented a brake assist system that determines that the driver is attempting a "panic stop" (by detecting that the brake pedal was depressed very quickly, unlike a normal stop where the pedal pressure would usually be gradually increased.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Some systems additionally monitor the rate at the accelerator was released, and/or the time between accelerator release and brake application) and the system automatically increases braking force where not enough pressure is applied.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Hard or panic braking on bumpy surfaces, because of the bumps causing the speed of the wheel(s) to become erratic may also trigger the ABS, sometimes causing the system to enter its ice mode, where the system severely limits maximum available braking power.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Nevertheless, ABS significantly improves safety and control for drivers in most on-road situations.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Anti-lock brakes are the subject of some experiments centred around risk compensation theory, which asserts that drivers adapt to the safety benefit of ABS by driving more aggressively.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In a Munich study, half a fleet of taxicabs was equipped with anti-lock brakes, while the other half had conventional brake systems.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The Insurance Institute for Highway Safety released a study in 2010 that found motorcycles with ABS 37% less likely to be involved in a fatal crash than models without ABS.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] On a motorcycle, an anti-lock brake system prevents the wheels of a motorcycle from locking during braking situations.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Based on information from wheel speed sensors the ABS unit adjusts the pressure of the brake fluid in order to keep traction during deceleration to avoid accidents.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Motorcycle ABS helps the rider to maintain stability during braking and to decrease the stopping distance.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] It provides traction even on low friction surfaces.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] While older ABS models are derived from cars, recent Motorcycle ABS is the result of research, oriented to the specifics of motorcycles in case of size, weight, and functionality.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] National and international organizations have evaluated Motorcycle ABS to be an important factor in increasing safety and reducing the number and severity of motorcycle crashes and collisions.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The European Commission passed legislation in 2012 that made the fitment with ABS for all new motorcycles above 125cc to be mandatory from 1 January 2016.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] *Consumer Reports* said in 2016 that "ABS is commonly offered on large, expensive models, but it has been spreading to several entry-level sportbikes and midsized bikes".
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In 1988, BMW introduced an electronic/hydraulic ABS for motorcycles, ten years after Daimler Benz and Bosch released the first four-wheel vehicle ABS for series production.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Motorcycles of BMW K100 series were optionally equipped with the ABS, which added 11 kg to the bike.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] It was developed together with FAG Kugelfischer and regulated the pressure in the braking circuits via a plunger piston.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Japanese manufacturers followed with an ABS option by 1992 on the Honda ST1100 and the Yamaha FJ1200.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Continental presented its first Motorcycle Integral ABS (MIB) in 2006.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] It has been developed in cooperation with BMW and weighed 2.3 kg.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] While the first generation of motorcycle ABS weighed around 11 kg, the generation (2011) presented by Bosch in 2009 weighs 0.7 kg (ABS base) and 1.6 kg (ABS enhanced) with integral braking.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Wheel speed sensors mounted on the front and rear wheel constantly measures the rotational speed of each wheel and delivers this information to an Electronic Control Unit (ECU).
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The ECU detects two things: 1) if the deceleration of one wheel exceeds a fixed threshold and 2) whether the brake slip, calculated based on information of both wheels, rises above a certain percentage and enters an unstable zone.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] These are indicators for a high possibility of a locking wheel.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] To countermeasure these irregularities the ECU signals the hydraulic unit to hold or to release pressure.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] After signals show the return to the stable zone, the pressure is increased again.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Past models used a piston for the control of the fluid pressure.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Most recent models regulate the pressure by rapidly opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] While the basic principle and architecture has been carried over from passenger car ABS, typical motorcycle characteristics have to be considered during the development and application processes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] One characteristic is the change of the dynamic wheel load during braking.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Compared to cars, the wheel load changes are more drastic, which can lead to a wheel lift up and a fall over.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This can be intensified by a soft suspension.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Some systems are equipped with a rear-wheel lift-off mitigation functionality.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] When the indicators of a possible rear lift-off are detected, the system releases brake pressure on the front wheel to counter this behavior.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Another difference is that in the case of the motorcycle the front wheel is much more important for stability than the rear wheel.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] If the front wheel locks up between 0.2-0.7s, it loses gyrostatic forces and the motorcycle starts to oscillate because of the increased influence of side forces operating on the wheel contact line.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The motorcycle becomes unstable and falls.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Electric vehicles can recapture the energy from rear wheel braking.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Contrary to how the wheels on cars and trains react collectively to brakes when applied, on motorcycles the rear wheel brake and front wheel brake are controlled separately.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] If the rider only brakes with one wheel, this braked wheel tends to lock up faster than if both brakes had been applied.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] A Combined Braking System therefore distributes the brake force also to the non-braked wheel to lower the possibility of a lock-up, increase deceleration and reduce suspension pitch.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] With a single [rear] CBS the brake pressure applied on the rear brake (pedal) is simultaneously distributed to the front wheel.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] A delay valve cuts the hydraulic pressure to assure that only when strong braking is applied, the pressure is also created at the front wheel.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Honda's first street motorcycle with a combined braking system (then called Unified Braking) was the 1983 GL1100.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This system was derived from the 1970s RCB1000 world endurance race bike.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Larger models with two front discs use a dual CBS System.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The system was first installed by Moto Guzzi in 1975.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Here, applied brake pressure at the front is also applied to the rear wheel and vice versa.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] If the front lever is applied, the pressure is built up at 4 of the 6 pots in the 2 calipers at the front.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] A secondary master cylinder at the front wheel distributes remaining pressure to the rear wheel through a proportional control valve and acts on 2 of the 3 calipers.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] If a strong brake force is applied at the rear wheel force is also distributed to 2 of the 6 pots of the front wheel.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] More modern dual CBS use front and rear calipers (and all pots) according to a preset load ratio of front to rear.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The proportioning was originally controlled by complex all-hydraulic systems interlinking the front and rear, with a fixed delay or by sensing weight distribution changes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] As early as 2001 an electrohydraulic system was introduced by BMW.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] CBS helps to reduce the danger of wheel locks and fall downs but in certain situations, it is possible that CBS causes a fall down.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] If brake pressure is distributed from the rear wheel to the front wheel and the friction of the surfaces changes suddenly (puddle, ice on the street) the front wheel might lock even if only the rear brake has been applied.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This would lead to a loss of stability and a fall down.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] CBS is therefore combined with ABS to avoid this on a motorcycle.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Different approaches are possible to realize this combination: *Without active pressure Build up* Single Version: A third additional channel links the rear wheel circuit through a delay valve to the front brake.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Strong brake pressure at the rear wheel (or both wheels) pressurizes both brake circuits however this pressure is adjusted according to wheel speed and brake slip.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The brake input of the rider is measured by pressure sensors and the information is provided to an ECU.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Together with the information of the wheel speed sensors, the ECU calculates the optimal distribution of pressure to prevent lockups and to provide the best possible deceleration.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Based on this output a motor for each wheel operates a pump that builds up and regulates the brake pressure on the wheel.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] This system offers a fast reaction time because of the brake by wire functionality.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The MIB (Motorcycle integral Braking system) from Continental Teves and the eCBS (electronic CBS) in the enhanced Motorcycle ABS from Bosch are results of another approach.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] These systems are based on the pump and valve approach.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Through additional valves, stronger pumps and a more powerful motor the system can actively build up pressure.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The input pressure of the rider is measured with pressure sensors at the lever and pedal.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The pump then builds up additional pressure adjusted to riding conditions.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] A partial integral system is designed for working in one direction only: front→rear or rear→front.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] A fully integrated system works in both directions.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Because these systems are electronically controlled and are able to build up pressure actively, they offer the opportunity to adjust the motorcycle braking behavior to the rider.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] CBS and ABS can be switched off by experienced riders and also different regulation modes with higher and lower thresholds can be chosen, such as the rain or slick mode in the BMW S1000RR.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] These studies caused the EU commission to initiate a legislative process in 2010 that was passed in 2012 and led to ABS for motorcycles above 125 cm3 becoming mandatory from 2016 onwards.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Organizations like the Fédération Internationale de l'Automobile and the Institute of advanced Motorists (IAM) demanded the implementation of this legislation already for 2015.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] On the other hand, some motorcycle riders are protesting against a compulsory ABS for all bikes because they call for a possibility to switch the system off, for off-road usage or for other reasons.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In 2011 the United Nations (UN) started the Decade of Action for Road Safety.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] The main goal is to save 5 million lives until 2020 through global cooperation.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] One part of their global plan is to: Encourage universal deployment of crash avoidance technologies with proven effectiveness such as Electronic Stability Control and Anti-Lock Braking Systems in motorcycles.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] In the United States, the NHTSA has mandated ABS in conjunction with electronic stability control under the provisions of FMVSS 126 as of September 1, 2012.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS is required in all new passenger cars produced in the EU since 2003.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Since 2016, the EU has required ABS on all new scooters, motorcycles, tricycles, and quads from 125 cc, otherwise CBS (or ABS).
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] 78, related to the braking of vehicles of categories L1, L2, L3, L4 and L5 (motorbikes) is applied by the European Union, Russia, Japan, Turkey, Ukraine, Australia and the United Kingdom.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Global technical regulation number 3 related to Motorcycle brake systems is applied by Canada, the European Union, Japan, Russia, and the United States.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Since 1 April 2019, India has required at least single-channel ABS on all new two-wheelers from 125 cc, otherwise CBS (or ABS).
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS has also been mandatory on all new cars and mini-buses from the same date.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Since 1 January 2019, Brazil has required ABS on all new motorcycles from 300 cc.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS has been mandatory on all new cars since January 2014.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] Since 1 January 2024, Argentina has required ABS on all new motorcycles from 250 cc, otherwise CBS (or front wheel ABS) for on-road between 50 and 250cc or their electric equivalents.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS has been mandatory on all new normal cars since January 2014.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] From February 2025, Chile will require ABS on all new motorcycles from 150 cc or 11 kW, otherwise CBS (or ABS) from 50 cc or 4 kW from February 2026.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] ABS has been mandatory on all new cars since October 2020.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] From October 2025, Colombia will require ABS on all new motorcycles from 150 cc or 11 kW, otherwise CBS (or ABS) from 50 cc or 4 kW.
[src:electronic-control-unit/anti-lock-braking-system] From March 2027, Colombia will require ABS on all new motorcycles from 125 cc, below that with CBS (or ABS).
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] An **automotive battery**, or **car battery**, is a rechargeable battery that is used to start a motor vehicle, and to power lights, screen wiper etc. while the engine is off.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Its main purpose is to provide an electric current to the electric-powered starting motor, which in turn starts the chemically-powered internal combustion engine that actually propels the vehicle.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Once the engine is running, power for the car's electrical systems is still supplied by the battery, with the alternator charging the battery as demands increase or decrease.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Typically, starting uses less than three percent of the battery capacity.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] For this reason, automotive batteries are designed to deliver maximum current for a short period of time.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] They are sometimes referred to as "SLI batteries" for this reason, for starting, lighting and ignition.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] SLI batteries are not designed for deep discharging, and a full discharge can reduce the battery's lifespan.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] As well as starting the engine, an SLI battery supplies the extra power necessary when the vehicle's electrical requirements exceed the supply from the charging system.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] It is also a stabilizer, evening out potentially damaging voltage spikes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] While the engine is running most of the power is provided by the alternator (or in older vehicles a generator or dynamo), which includes a voltage regulator to keep the output between 13.5 and 14.5 V.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Modern SLI batteries are lead-acid type, using six series-connected cells to provide a nominal 12-volt system (in most passenger vehicles and light trucks), or twelve cells for a 24-volt system in heavy trucks or earth-moving equipment, for example.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Gas explosions can occur at the negative electrode where hydrogen gas can build up due to blocked battery vents or a poorly ventilated setting, combined with an ignition source.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Explosions during engine start-up are typically associated with corroded or dirty battery posts.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] A 1993 study by the US National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said that 31% of vehicle battery explosion injuries occurred while charging the battery.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Close to two-thirds of those injured suffered chemical burns, and nearly three-fourths suffered eye injuries, among other possible injuries.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Electric vehicles (EVs) are powered by a high-voltage electric vehicle battery, but they usually have an automotive battery as well, so that they can use standard automotive accessories which are designed to run on 12 V.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Unlike conventional, internal combustion engined vehicles, EVs don't charge the auxiliary battery with an alternator—instead, they use a DC-to-DC converter to step down the high voltage to the required float-charge voltage (typically around 14 V).
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Further, an electric vehicle does not have a starter motor, thus needs only a limited amount of power and energy from its auxiliary battery.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] As such, Tesla introduced in 2021 a lithium-ion auxiliary battery storing only 99 Wh of energy.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Early cars did not have batteries, as their electrical systems were limited.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Electric power for the ignition was provided by a magneto, the engine was started with a crank, headlights were gas-powered and a bell or bulb-horn was used instead of an electric horn.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Car batteries became widely used around 1920 as cars became equipped with electric starter motors.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] The first starting and charging systems were designed to be 6-volt and positive-ground systems, with the vehicle's chassis directly connected to the positive battery terminal.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Today, almost all road vehicles have a negative ground system.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] The negative battery terminal is connected to the car's chassis.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] The Hudson Motor Car Company was the first to use a standardized battery in 1918 when they started using Battery Council International batteries.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] BCI is the organization that sets the dimensional standards for batteries.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Cars used 6 V electrical systems and batteries until the mid-1950s.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] The changeover from 6 to 12 V happened when bigger engines with higher compression ratios required more electrical power to start.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Smaller cars, which required less power to start stayed with 6 V longer, for example the Volkswagen Beetle in the mid-1960s and the Citroën 2CV in 1970.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] The AGM sealed battery (for automobiles), which did not require refilling, was invented in 1971.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] In the 1990s a 42V electrical system standard was proposed.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] It was intended to allow more powerful electrically driven accessories, and lighter automobile wiring harnesses.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] However, the availability of higher-efficiency motors, new wiring techniques, and digital controls, and a focus on hybrid vehicle systems that use high-voltage starter/generators have largely eliminated the push for switching the main automotive voltages.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] In 2023 Tesla started deliveries of their Cybertruck that uses a 48-volt electrical system, reducing 70% of the wiring in the vehicle.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] An automobile battery is an example of a wet cell battery, with six cells.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Each cell of a lead storage battery consists of alternate plates made of a lead alloy grid filled with sponge lead plates (cathode) or coated with lead dioxide (anode).
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Each cell is filled with a sulfuric acid solution, which is the electrolyte.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Initially, cells each had a filler cap, through which the electrolyte level could be viewed and which allowed water to be added to the cell.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] The filler cap had a small vent hole which allowed hydrogen gas generated during charging to escape from the cell.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] The cells are connected by short heavy straps from the positive plates of one cell to the negative plates of the adjacent cell.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] A pair of heavy terminals, plated with lead to resist corrosion, are mounted at the top, sometimes the side, of the battery.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Early auto batteries used hard rubber cases and wooden plate separators.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Modern units use plastic cases and woven sheets to prevent the plates of a cell from touching and short-circuiting.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] In the past, auto batteries required regular inspection and maintenance to replace water that was decomposed during the operation of the battery.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] "Low-maintenance" (sometimes called "zero-maintenance") batteries use a different alloy for the plate elements, reducing the amount of water decomposed on charging.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] A modern battery may not require additional water over its useful life; some types eliminate the individual filler caps for each cell.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] A weakness of these batteries is that they are very intolerant of deep discharge, such as when the car battery is completely drained by leaving the lights on.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] This coats the lead plate electrodes with lead sulfate deposits and can reduce the battery's lifespan by a third or more.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries, also known as absorbed glass mat (AGM) batteries are more tolerant of deep discharge but are more expensive.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] VRLA batteries do not permit addition of water to the cell.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] The cells each have an automatic pressure release valve, to protect the case from rupture on severe overcharge or internal failure.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] A VRLA battery cannot spill its electrolyte which makes it particularly useful in vehicles such as motorcycles.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Batteries are typically made of six galvanic cells in a series circuits.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Each cell provides 2.1 volts for a total of 12.6 volts at full charge.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] During discharge, at the negative (lead) terminal a chemical reaction releases electrons to the external circuit, and at the positive (lead oxide) terminal another chemical reaction absorbs electrons from the external circuit.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] This drives the electrons through the external circuit wire (an electrical conductor) to produce an electric current (electricity).
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] As the battery discharges, the acid of the electrolyte reacts with the materials of the plates, changing their surface to lead sulfate.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] When the battery is recharged, the chemical reaction is reversed: the lead sulfate reforms into lead dioxide.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] With the plates restored to their original condition, the process may be repeated.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Some vehicles use other starter batteries.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] For weight savings, the 2010 Porsche 911 GT3 RS has a lithium-ion battery as an option; from 2018 onward, all Kia Niro conventional hybrids feature one as well.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Heavy vehicles may have two batteries in series for a 24 V system or may have series-parallel groups of batteries supplying 24 V.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Batteries are grouped by physical size, type and placement of the terminals, and mounting style.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Battery Council International (BCI) group size specifies a battery's physical dimensions, such as length, width, and height.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] These groups are determined by the organization.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Ampere hours (Ah or A·h) is a unit related to the energy storage capacity of the battery.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] This rating is required by law in Europe.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] The ampere hour rating represents the total current delivered over a period of 20 hours before voltage drops below 10.5 volts while operating at a temperature of 80 °F (26.6 °C).
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] In theory, at 80 °F, a 100 Ah battery should be able to continuously provide 5 amps for 20 hours while maintaining a voltage of at least 10.5 volts.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] The relationship between the Ah capacity and the discharge rate is not linear; as the discharge rate is increased, the capacity decreases.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] A battery with a 100 Ah rating generally will not be able to maintain a voltage above 10.5 volts for 10 hours while being discharged at constant rate of 10 amps.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Capacity also decreases with temperature.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Excess heat is a main cause of battery failures, as when the electrolyte evaporates due to high temperatures, decreasing the effective surface area of the plates exposed to the electrolyte, and leading to sulfation.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Grid corrosion rates increase with temperature.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Also low temperatures can lead to battery failure.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] If the battery is discharged to the point where it can't start the engine, the engine can be jump started via an external source of power.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Once running, the engine can recharge the battery, if the alternator and charging system are undamaged.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Corrosion at the battery terminals can prevent a car from starting due to electrical resistance, which can be prevented by the proper application of dielectric grease.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Sulfation is when the electrodes become coated with a hard layer of lead sulfate, which weakens the battery.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Sulfation can happen when battery is not fully charged and remains discharged.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Sulfated batteries should be charged slowly to prevent damage.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] SLI batteries (starting, lighting, and ignition) are not designed for deep discharge, and their life is reduced when subjected to this.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Starting batteries have plates designed for increased surface area and thus high instant current capability, whereas marine (hybrid) and deep cycle types will have thicker plates and more room at the bottom of the plates for spent plate material to gather before shorting the cell.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Car batteries using lead-antimony plates require regular topping-up with pure water to replace water lost due to electrolysis and evaporation.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] By changing the alloying element to calcium, more recent designs have reduced the rate of water loss.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Modern car batteries have reduced maintenance requirements, and may not provide caps for addition of water to the cells.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Such batteries include extra electrolyte above the plates to allow for losses during the battery life.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Some battery manufacturers include a built-in hydrometer to show the state of charge of the battery.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] The primary wear-out mechanism is the shedding of active material from the battery plates, which accumulates at the bottom of the cells and which may eventually short-circuit the plates.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] This can be substantially reduced by enclosing one set of plates in plastic separator bags, made from a permeable material.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] This allows the electrolyte and ions to pass through but keeps the sludge build up from bridging the plates.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] The sludge largely consists of lead sulfate, which is produced at both electrodes.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Battery recycling of automotive batteries reduces the need for resources required for the manufacture of new batteries, diverts toxic lead from landfills, and prevents the risk of improper disposal.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Once a lead–acid battery ceases to hold a charge, it is deemed a used lead-acid battery (ULAB), which is classified as hazardous waste under the Basel Convention.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] The 12-volt car battery is the most recycled product in the world, according to the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] In the U.S. alone, about 130 million auto batteries a year are replaced, and 99 percent of them are turned in for recycling.[1] However, the recycling may be done incorrectly in unregulated environments.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] As part of global waste trade, ULABs are shipped from industrialized countries to developing countries for disassembly and recuperation of the contents.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] About 97 percent of the lead can be recovered.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Pure Earth estimates that over 12 million people in developing countries are affected by lead contamination from ULAB processing.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] ULAB recycling has been used as an example supporting the pollution haven hypothesis.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-battery] Following this change, American exports of used lead-acid batteries to Mexico increased four-fold, which was followed by a significant increase in babies born with low birth weight to mothers living within a two-mile (3.2 km) radius of Mexican battery-recycling plants.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Electronic systems have become an increasingly large component of the cost of an automobile, from only around 1% of its value in 1950 to around 30% in 2010.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Modern electric cars rely on power electronics for the main propulsion motor control, as well as managing the battery system.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Future autonomous cars will rely on powerful computer systems, an array of sensors, networking, and satellite navigation, all of which will require electronics.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] The earliest electronic systems available as factory installations were vacuum tube car radios, starting in the early 1930s.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] The development of semiconductors after World War II greatly expanded the use of electronics in automobiles, with solid-state diodes making the automotive alternator the standard after about 1960, and the first transistorized ignition systems appearing in 1963.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] The emergence of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology led to the development of modern automotive electronics.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Dawon Kahng summarized in a Bell Labs memo the achievement: E.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Ligenza who developed the diffusion processes, and H.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] This led to the development of the power MOSFET by Hitachi in 1969, and the single-chip microprocessor by Federico Faggin, Marcian Hoff, Masatoshi Shima and Stanley Mazor at Intel in 1971.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] The development of MOS integrated circuit (MOS IC) chips and microprocessors made a range of automotive applications economically feasible in the 1970s.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] In the early 1970s, the Japanese electronics industry began producing integrated circuits and microcontrollers for the Japanese automobile industry, used for in-car entertainment, automatic wipers, electronic locks, dashboard, and engine control.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] The Ford EEC (Electronic Engine Control) system, which utilized the Toshiba TLCS-12 PMOS microprocessor, went into mass production in 1975.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] In 1978, the Cadillac Seville featured a "trip computer" based on a 6802 microprocessor.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Electronically-controlled ignition and fuel injection systems allowed automotive designers to achieve vehicles meeting requirements for fuel economy and lower emissions, while still maintaining high levels of performance and convenience for drivers.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Today's automobiles contain a dozen or more processors, in functions such as engine management, transmission control, climate control, antilock braking, passive safety systems, navigation, and other functions.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] The power MOSFET and the microcontroller, a type of single-chip microcomputer, led to significant advances in electric vehicle technology.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] MOSFET power converters allowed operation at much higher switching frequencies, made it easier to drive, reduced power losses, and significantly reduced prices, while single-chip microcontrollers could manage all aspects of the drive control and had the capacity for battery management.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] MOSFETs are used in vehicles such as automobiles, cars, trucks, electric vehicles, and smart cars.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] MOSFETs are used for the electronic control unit (ECU), while the power MOSFET and IGBT are used as the load drivers for automotive loads such as motors, solenoids, ignition coils, relays, heaters and lamps.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] In 2000, the average mid-range passenger vehicle had an estimated $100–200 of power semiconductor content, increasing by a potential 3–5 times for electric and hybrid vehicles.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] As of 2017, the average vehicle has over 50 actuators, typically controlled by power MOSFETs or other power semiconductor devices.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Another important technology that enabled modern highway-capable electric cars is the lithium-ion battery.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] It was invented by John Goodenough, Rachid Yazami and Akira Yoshino in the 1980s, and commercialized by Sony and Asahi Kasei in 1991.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] The lithium-ion battery was responsible for the development of electric vehicles capable of long-distance travel, by the 2000s.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] On average, a 2020s car has 50–150 chips, according to Chris Isidore of CNN Business.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] One of the most demanding electronic parts of an automobile is the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Engine controls demand one of the highest real-time deadlines, as the engine itself is a very fast and complex part of the automobile.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Of all the electronics in any car, the computing power of the engine control unit is the highest, typically a 32-bit processor.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] A modern car may have up to 100 ECU's and a commercial vehicle up to 40.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Many more engine parameters are actively monitored and controlled in real-time.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] There are about 20 to 50 that measure pressure, temperature, flow, engine speed, oxygen level and NOx level plus other parameters at different points within the engine.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] All these sensor signals are sent to the ECU, which has the logic circuits to do the actual controlling.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] The ECU output is connected to different actuators for the throttle valve, EGR valve, rack (in VGTs), fuel injector (using a pulse-width modulated signal), dosing injector and more.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] There are about 20 to 30 actuators in all.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] These control the transmission system, mainly the shifting of the gears for better shift comfort and to lower torque interrupt while shifting.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Automatic transmissions use controls for their operation, and also many semi-automatic transmissions having a fully automatic clutch or a semi-auto clutch (declutching only).
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] The engine control unit and the transmission control exchange messages, sensor signals and control signals for their operation.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] All of the above systems form an infotainment system.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Developmental methods for these systems vary according to each manufacturer.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Different tools are used for both hardware and software development.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] These are new generation hybrid ECUs that combine the functionalities of multiple ECUs of Infotainment Head Unit, Advanced Driver Assistance Systems (ADAS), Instrument Cluster, Rear Camera/Parking Assist, Surround View Systems etc.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] This saves on the cost of electronics as well as mechanical/physical parts like interconnects across ECUs etc.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] There is also a more centralized control so data can be seamlessly exchanged between the systems.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Given the complexity of this hybrid system, a lot more rigor is needed to validate the system for robustness, safety and security.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] For example, if the infotainment system's application which could be running an open-source Android OS is breached, there could be possibility of hackers to take control of the car remotely and potentially misuse it for anti-social activities.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Typically so, usage of a hardware+software enabled hypervisors are used to virtualize and create separate trust and safety zones that are immune to each other's failures or breaches.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Lot of work is happening in this area and potentially will have such systems soon if not already.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] In order to minimize the risk of dangerous failures, safety-related electronic systems have to be developed following the applicable product liability requirements.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Disregard for, or inadequate application of these standards can lead to not only personal injuries, but also severe legal and economic consequences such as product cancellations or recalls.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] The IEC 61508 standard, generally applicable to electrical/electronic/programmable safety-related products, is only partially adequate for automotive-development requirements.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Consequently, for the automotive industry, this standard is replaced by the existing ISO 26262, currently released as a Final Draft International Standard (FDIS).
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] ISO/DIS 26262 describes the entire product life-cycle of safety-related electrical/electronic systems for road vehicles.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] It has been published as an international standard in its final version in November 2011.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] The implementation of this new standard will result in modifications and various innovations in the automobile electronics development process, as it covers the complete product life-cycle from the concept phase until its decommissioning.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] As more functions of the automobile are connected to short- or long-range networks, cybersecurity of systems against unauthorized modification is required.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] With critical systems such as engine controls, transmission, airbags, and braking connected to internal diagnostic networks, remote access could result in a malicious intruder altering the function of systems or disabling them, possibly causing injuries or fatalities.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Every new interface presents a new "attack surface".
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] The same facility that allows the owner to unlock and start a car from a smartphone app also presents risks due to remote access.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Auto manufacturers may protect the memory of various control microprocessors both to secure them from unauthorized changes and also to ensure only manufacturer-authorized facilities can diagnose or repair the vehicle.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] Systems such as keyless entry rely on cryptographic techniques to ensure "replay" or "man-in-the-middle attacks" attacks cannot record sequences to allow later break-in to the automobile.
[src:electronic-control-unit/automotive-electronics] In 2015 the German general automobile club commissioned an investigation of the vulnerabilities of one manufacturer's electronics system, which could have led to such exploits as unauthorized remote unlocking of the vehicle.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] An **electronic control unit** (**ECU**), also known as an **electronic control module** (**ECM**), is an embedded system in automotive electronics that controls one or more of the electrical systems or subsystems in a car or other motor vehicle.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] These ECUs together are sometimes referred to collectively as **the car's computer** though technically they are all separate computers, not a single one.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] Sometimes an assembly incorporates several individual control modules (a PCM often controls both the engine and the transmission).
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] Some modern motor vehicles have up to 150 ECUs.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] Embedded software in ECUs continues to increase in line count, complexity, and sophistication.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] Managing the increasing complexity and number of ECUs in a vehicle has become a key challenge for original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] The development of an ECU involves both hardware and software required to perform the functions expected from that particular module.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] Automotive ECU's are being developed following the V-model.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] Recently the trend is to dedicate a significant amount of time and effort to develop safe modules by following standards like ISO 26262.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] It is rare that a module is developed fully from scratch.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] The design is generally iterative and improvements are made to both the hardware and software.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] The development of most ECUs is carried out by Tier 1 suppliers based on specifications provided by the OEM.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] As part of the development cycle, manufacturers perform detailed FMEAs and other failure analyses to catch failure modes that can lead to unsafe conditions or driver annoyance.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] Extensive testing and validation activities are carried out as part of the production part approval process to gain the confidence of the hardware and software.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] On-board diagnostics or OBD help provide specific data related to which system or component failed or caused a failure during run time and help perform repairs.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] Some people may wish to modify their ECU so as to be able to add or change functionality.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] However modern ECUs come equipped with protection locks to prevent users from modifying the circuit or exchange chips.
[src:electronic-control-unit/electronic-control-unit] The protection locks are a form of digital rights management (DRM), the circumventing of which is illegal in certain jurisdictions.
